Progress Report #1

Data Pre-Processing

Importing Data

A CSV file was created from the provided data call R file for the project (10017_USCDAT_v01_20210609_2220_R_data_call_Jaxon_Abercrombie). The file contains the combined dataset, and it solely contains data for eligible participants. All duplicate rows were removed to keep the dataset cleaner and duplicates would skew data when creating summary statistics.

# Read in the created CSV file
data <- read.csv("distinct_combined_data.csv")

The data set contains 48324 observations and 165 variables. These components denote that there are 48324 eligible participants for analysis and up to 165 available variables for each participant. The variables of this dataset primarily relate to birth and death dates, hospital admission and discharge dates, demographic characteristics (age, ethnicity, race), medical history (past diagnoses), health behaviors (sleep, diet, smoking), and metrics like height and weight. variables were extracted from questionnaires and other information sources for patients, and data was made available by the California Teachers Study.

Additionally, the number of missing values were counted across all variables in the dataset. Fortunately, the majority of missing values are attributable to a missing date for a procedure a participant never had, if questionnaires were not filled out by a participant entirely, or if a patient did not have a death date due to their current state of being alive. These values would be investigated further and handled later in this report.


Identifying Main Variables of Interest

Especially because over 150 variables may be overwhelming to look through, a certain focus would be decided by reducing the number of variables of primary interest looked at in this progress report. Tableau Reader was used to look at variables and their respective relationships with one another. Of course, variables could be added or removed from this preliminary and exhaustive list depending on reassessment of variables. After using Tableau and browsing data dictionaries, the variables listed below were the main ones of interest:

  • Variables related to birth, death and age

    • Date of birth

    • Birthplace

    • Date of death (as applicable)

    • Cause of death (as applicable)

    • Deceased

    • Age at baseline

  • Variables related to demography and personal characteristics

    • SES quartile

    • Participant race

    • Ethnic category

    • Live near oil refinery

    • Height, weight, and BMI

  • Variables related to medical history and behaviors

    • Procedures (hysterectomy, mastectomy, oophorectomy, mammogram)

    • Diagnoses (ICD codes, major diagnosis category code, cancers, diabetes, stroke, heart attack, high blood pressure, asthma)

    • Medications (total years used contraception, high blood pressure medicine, NSAID, insulin, ace inhibitor, tamoxifen, oral steroids, inhaler, antidepressant, cholesterol lowering medication)

    • Behaviors (physical activity, standing and sitting hours, diet, smoking, alcohol usage)

    • Others (menarche, pregnancy)

  • Variables related to visits, facilities, and costs

    • Payer category code

    • Facility county code

    • Facility zip code

    • Patient care type

    • Source admission code

    • Participant length of stay

    • Admission type and date

    • Discharge date


Ensuring Variable Consistency

After deciding which variables would be looked at initially, it was important to understand how variables can be made consistent in their values and types as seen in the data dictionaries. While many variables follow either a 0 and 1 binary value format, some follow an A and B or Y and N value format as well. It is crucial to keep in mind that A is equivalent to Y and 1 moving forward. That way, when reporting outputs and understanding models, there is no mix up. Furthermore, some binary variables technically included third options to indicate a participant not knowing their status, often denoted as Z.

Additionally, to make sure variables were following their intended variable type (num, char, date, etc.), column types for each variable were compared to data dictionaries. Whenever necessary, categorical variables used would be transformed into factor variables later on, like ages of mother at birth or deceased.


Handling Missing Values and Outliers

For missing values, the only variables that could possible undergo imputation were variables that have missing values on the basis of actually being missing. In other words, values for dates or choosing a random value for a participants diabetes status would not be acceptable. On the other hand, values that have more potential to be inferred, like sleep hours, based on the average or median sleep hour values would be more acceptable here. That would be done categorically, like imputing average sitting hours by gender. Before any handling, it was crucial to note that some values would be missing because such values were never available. For example, if a participant did not smoke or drink, there would naturally be missing values for smoking and drinking related variables for participants who never partook in such activities.

To ensure there are no painfully obvious outliers, minimum and maximum values would be assessed for each variable used. The provided data dictionaries would be come helpful here once again, as ranges of values are listed in the dictionaries to ensure no values are too small or large upon comparison between dataset and dictionary. Code output is hidden to avoid extraneous length to report.

Looking at missing value counts, the percent of missing values are often below 5% for all investigated variables. The only variables that may be of concern with the large number of missing values are those related to smoking, which near almost 35,000 missing values each. However, such values are missing likely because of values not being applicable (ex: the participant is not a smoker and therefore does not engage with smoking). 30686 people evidently have not smoked, for example, which matches up well with the findings related to the large number of missing values for smoking-related variables. Most variables would be kept without imputation because of the low percent of NAs, and the capabilities of some models to handle missing values would be capitalized on. Especially to not introduce bias and shrink error artificially, imputation will be avoided for now. In any case poor model performance can be attributed to an abundance of missing values, such imputation can be carried out later.

All numerical values and their respective minimums and maximums were compared to provided value ranges in data dictionary. None were outside of expected boundaries. Additionally, no particular outliers were found in visualizations made in Tableau Reader.


Creation of New Variables

Once all variables were looked over to gauge completeness and consistency, creating new variables was the next step involved. From variables like birth date, admission date, discharge date, death date, diagnoses, and medications, many others could be created. The list of variables and their description are below:

  • Number of ICD Diagnoses:

    • Counts number of ICD diagnoses from the maximum five given

    • To see if number of diagnoses impacts risk of death significantly

  • Time to death

    • Looks at how many days from discharge it takes for a given participant to pass away

  • Time to death (categorical)

    • Looks at whether someone passed within the first month, between the second and sixth month, etc.

    • Will be helpful when sorting instances to use for models (ex: solely using 0-30 days, etc.)

  • Seasonality of death, admission, and discharge

    • To see if there are any interesting seasonal patterns in when most people are admitted, discharged, or pass away

    • Uses months to figure out season; not using solstices for ease of boundaries

  • Age at time of death

    • Uses birth and death date (where applicable) to get the age at which someone passed away

    • That way, if their age is extremely high, death may be attributable to age

    • Additionally, this gives more insight than age at baseline in relation to death

  • Number of medications taken

    • Counts how many medications a person takes daily (self-reported)

    • Used to investigate whether taking multiple medications makes for higher risk of death

# Number of ICD diagnoses total
for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
  data$icd_count[i] <- sum(!is.na(data[i,118:122]))
}


# Time to death (days from discharge to death)
data <- data %>%
  mutate(days_discharge_to_death = 
           as.numeric(as.Date(data$date_of_death_dt) 
                      - as.Date(data$discharge_dt)))


# Time to death (as categories)
data <- 
  data %>%
  mutate(days_discharge_to_death_cat = case_when(
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 0:30 ~ "0-1 mo",
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 31:180 ~ "1-6 mo",
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 181:365 ~ "6 mo to 1 yr",
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 366:730 ~ "1 yr to 2 yrs",
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 731:1825 ~ "2 yrs to 5 yrs",
    days_discharge_to_death %in% 731:10000 ~ "5 yrs+"
  ))


# Seasonality of death (summer, winter, fall, spring)
data <- 
  data %>%
  mutate(date_of_death_dt = as.Date(date_of_death_dt))

data <- 
  data %>%
  mutate(season_death = case_when(
    month(date_of_death_dt) %in% 1:3 ~ "winter",
    month(date_of_death_dt) %in% 4:6 ~ "spring",
    month(date_of_death_dt) %in% 7:9 ~ "summer",
    month(date_of_death_dt) %in% 10:12 ~ "fall"
  ))


# Seasonality of admission (summer, winter, fall, spring)
data <- 
  data %>%
  mutate(season_admission = case_when(
    month(admission_dt) %in% 1:3 ~ "winter",
    month(admission_dt) %in% 4:6 ~ "spring",
    month(admission_dt) %in% 7:9 ~ "summer",
    month(admission_dt) %in% 10:12 ~ "fall"
  ))


# Seasonality of discharge (summer, winter, fall, spring)
data <- 
  data %>%
  mutate(season_discharge = case_when(
    month(discharge_dt) %in% 1:3 ~ "winter",
    month(discharge_dt) %in% 4:6 ~ "spring",
    month(discharge_dt) %in% 7:9 ~ "summer",
    month(discharge_dt) %in% 10:12 ~ "fall"
  ))


# Age at time of death
data <- data %>%
  mutate(age_at_death = 
           (as.numeric(as.Date(data$date_of_death_dt) 
                      - as.Date(data$date_of_birth_dt)))/365)


# Total number of daily medications taken
for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
  data$meds_count[i] <- sum(data[i,89:96] == "Y")
}

From the plots above, the main takeaways are:

  • Age at baseline is relatively normally distirbuted around the age of 60, while the age at death is visibly negatively skewed with most deaths occurring after about 80 years of age

  • Many participants die within the first year after being discharged from the hospital, as well as as far as 5 years after discharge

    • The relatively steady distribution across the discharge to death categories warrants more stratification or model-building that specifically uses the categories in an isolated way

  • Majority of participants do not take daily medications

    • Whether or not they are prescribed to is not known (later variables such as a diabetes diagnosis, which often assumes a prescription of insulin, and whether or not insulin is taken daily) can create a variable related to adherence to medication at some point

  • A large percentage of participants experience the project maximum of 5 diagnoses

  • The participants in the study are not heavy alcohol drinkers

  • Many participants are sedentary (no strenuous/moderate exercise), while somereceive a moderate amount of 1-5 hours a week

    • I would like to see what categorizes people as sedentary and more prone to die

  • Most participants get a healthy 7-9 hours of rest a night, with some only getting 5-6 and a small amount sleeping even 3-4 hours a day/night

  • Most participants have never smoked before, with some having quit and a small proportion still smoking

  • Most participants belong to the SES category of 4, which denotes a high status

  • Most participants only stay in their respective hospitals for less than 5 days

  • The most common causes of death are Alzheimers, atherosclerotic heart disease, breast cancer, lung cancer, and stroke

  • Facilities were most often in Los Angeles, San Diego, Orange, Santa Clara, and Alameda counties

    • This is incredibly biased from population size, so it would be interesting to do more analysis looking a means to standardize county facilities based on how many facilities are available

    • Would want to further this and see if where care is provided has impact on someones survival chances (ex: including in logistic regression and comparing magnitude of coefficients)

  • The majority of the population has Medicare as its payer, followed by private health insurance

  • Without any stratification of participants, there are no noticeable differences seasonally for death, admission, or discharge; most counts appear relatively equal

From the plots above, the main takeaways are:

  • The age at which someone passes seems to be strongly associated as shown by the boxplot; the older someone is, the greater chance they will pass away

  • The number of diagnoses is generally higher in the deceased participants, as seen with less variance in the boxplot created

  • Deceased participants were taking daily medication more than those alive

  • Generally, deceased participants had longer hospital stays

  • There seems to be no relationship between a participants age at baseline and their number of days to death after discharge

  • The number of diagnoses someone has does not seem to greatly impact the number of days until death after discharge

  • The number of medications someone takes daily does not seem to greatly impact the number of days until death after discharge

  • Deceased participants are slightly less physically active than those alive, which makes sedentary behavior appear to be less of a risk for death

  • Relative to their respective sizes/number of participants, the deceased categories seem similarly distributed across smoking categories

  • Alcoholic intake did not seem to be much different for deceased status

  • BMI did not seem to have an associated with deceased status

In addition to these plots, more will be made in Tableau Reader to accelerate the process of finding interesting associations between the many variables and deceased status

Summary Statistics

Summary statistics for main numerical variables are below.

### TO BE USED FOR ALL TABLES ###
# Initialize data frame for summary statistics
datasum <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 6, nrow = 0))

# Figure out column numbers to use in vector for variable list below
# ex: which(colnames(data)=="sleep_hrs")

# Create variable list for iteration function below to build df
varlist <- c(25,172,42,43, 44, 167, 101, 166, 173, 86, 57)

# Function to calculate summary stats and append to empty data frame
sumstat <- function(df, df2, varlist) {
  for (i in varlist) {
  varname <- colnames(df)[i]
  varmin <- min(df[,i], na.rm = T)
  varmean <- mean(df[,i], na.rm = T)
  varsd <- sd(df[,i], na.rm = T)
  varmed <- median(df[,i], na.rm = T)
  varmax <- max(df[,i], na.rm = T)
  stats <- c(varname, varmin, varmean, varsd, varmed, varmax)
  df2 <- rbind(df2, stats)
  }
  return(df2)
}

# Column names list to rename each data frame upon finalizing
colnames1 <- c("Variable", "Min", "Mean", "SD", "Median", "Max")

    kbl(caption = type) %>%

  }

After looking through some models by domain and making a combined model based on other models outputs, my thoughts as of now with this report are as follows:

  • BMI seems to do well in models, as obesity is certainly a contributor for death

  • I want to make sure to use patient disposition codes and major diagnosis codes, as these variables as factor variables help distinguish reasons for admission and ailments that may be easier to interpret in later parts of the project

  • The model dealing with patient behaviors appears to have the lowest AIC, which potentially explains that health behavior variables make for better fit models

  • The amount of medications taken daily and the number of diagnoses a person has seemingly are important as well

  • Age is an obvious predictor of death, since, as one gets older, they have greater potential to pass away

  • Certain diets (will have to check correlation with BMI) may be good indicators of longevity regardless of hospital visit

  • Antidepressant medication, which helps draw in a mental health variable for the model(s), is something I want to investigate more as well

  • Child bearing also would be interesting to maintain in models, since having a kid is a physical toll as well as a sustained stressor over time in most cases
